shared_text:
Kim Loghry Cravens is with Bubba Winningham and 10 others.
August 28 at 5:13 PM ·

Here’s a BIG shout out to our I Make a Difference award winners at last night’s monthly PCSS BOE meeting. Brandon Smith was nominated by Bubba Winningham for all his hard work at the emergency response center after the tornado. We are grateful for all that Brandon does for our school system and community!! Also nominated by Jill Ramsey were Autumn Reagan AES, Lindsay Spain & Allison Ledford PSES, and Sarah Vaughn BPS. These ladies all went above and beyond for remote learners not only in Putnam County, but across the state working in conjunction with PBS and making teaching videos! We are very thankful for all of their hard work!!! Congratulations to all the winners!! We are blessed to have you!! And thank you to Dawn Myers Fry for serving as chair for the last two years! We look forward to working with new chair Lynn McHenry!!

COOKEVILLE HIGH SCHOOL REMOTE LEARNING STUDENTS
If you chose remote learning as your preferred method of learning for the beginning of the 2020-2021 school year, schedules will be available in PowerSchool July 30th for those who did not pick up schedules at Cookeville High School. Please email your teachers to access your Google Classroom and receive any remote learning instructions specific to each class. If you indicated on the google form that you are in need of a device and/or internet access, those items may be picked up from the library on Friday July 31st from 9:00-11:00am. Face coverings are required and please practice social distancing guidelines while picking up your device.

shared_text:
Putnam County Schools (TN) School System published a note.
July 7, 2014 at 7:59 PM ·

PCSS Social Media - Guidelines for Participation - Updated 07/28/2019
The PCSS Facebook page is a limited public forum, limited to the discussion of matters related to the Putnam County School System Social Media websites.


We encourage you to submit your questions, comments, and concerns via the Contact Us button provided on the page.  We will respond directly to questions, comments, and concerns submitted this way.  Comments or questions posted on posts on the page are generally only visible to the person making the post and will not get a response. Personal conversations should occur on your own page.
This site does not circumvent or supersede PCSS's normal business practices or processes. For example, reports of issues with personnel, responses to requests for proposals, invitations for bid, or other competitive procurements are not properly submitted via this site. Content submitted to this site is not legal notice to PCSS. For example, notice may NOT be given to PCSS under the Local Government Tort Claims Act through this site.  PCSS social media sites are family-friendly and education based. We are here to support our students, staff, and community, however, use of any district logo or image on one’s personal social networking site is prohibited. We understand that social media is a 24/7 medium; however, our moderation capabilities are not. We may not see every inappropriate comment right away, and we are trusting in the maturity of our community to ignore personal attacks and negative speech or respond politely. Comments are now limited to tagging others to share information. PCSS reserves the right to limit or delete comments, without notice, that:Are off topic;Are solicitations or advertisements for commercial products or services;Infringe on copyrights or trademarks;Are obscene under legal standards; orSpeech that is otherwise unprotected by the First Amendment that PCSS deems inappropriate for the site.
PCSS reserves the right to delete comments that are more than thirty (30) days old. By virtue of providing content to this site, you agree that you have no expectation of privacy in the information provided. PCSS is not responsible for and does not endorse any links embedded in comments posted to this site by third parties.

The new facilitator team is Kayla Satterfield & Nathan Twitty (ES), Lacy Means & Johnny Harrison (MS), Ciara Pitman & Kayla Radford (HS). CHS New Student/ Transfer Registration Information

Thursday, July 16th (9:00 am- Noon) Transfer Registration for students (grades 9-12) who have not pre registered at CHS for the 2020- 2021 school year. CHS will practice social distancing and follow all CDC guidelines. We encourage students and parents/ guardians to do the same.

What do I need to bring?

Students will need to attend with a parent or guardian (proof of custody if applicable), have two proofs of residency, an immunization record, birth certificate, social security card, attendance/report card or transcript from previous school. Not having these documents may delay the enrollment process. At the time of registration, students will be advised where and when to pick up their schedules.

Putnam County, Tennessee - Randy Porter, Mayor
May 5 at 8:06 PM ·

😷 PUBLIC MASK DISTRIBUTION 😷
The Tennessee Department of Health is issuing cloth masks to all citizens in the State of Tennessee. In Putnam County, Emergency Management and Health Department officials will be working together to distribute masks, free of charge, beginning Thursday May 7th.

Mask distribution will take place on weekdays, beginning Thursday, from 9am - 3pm at the Putnam County Fairgrounds (located at 155 Fairground Street in Cookeville). Please note the directions on the map: you will enter Fairground Street from S. Walnut Avenue, then continue around the fairground property to the distribution point. Please only enter from S. Walnut Avenue and follow any signs directing you around the venue.

Tips for a quick trip:
* Please know how many masks you need for the members of your household.
* Please stay in your vehicle
* Please keep your windows rolled up until you reach the distribution point
* Please do not get extra masks - only get the number needed for your household

For Sale At Public Auction
May 30, 2020 at 10:00 a.m.
Cookeville High School Campus

This beautiful home will be auctioned off at 10 a.m. on May 30, 2020. This 3 BR, 2 BA has 1,560 sq. ft. and measures 26’ x 60’. ATTENTION: PCSS Statewide Dual Credit Students
The TNDOE, in conjunction with TBR, will offer students an opportunity to test this upcoming fall.TBR will work with schools directly to create testing rosters during July and August and the testing window will be open from September 1-30, 2020. Additionally, review materials will be provided inAugust for students and teachers to prepare prior to the testing window.
Only students who would like the chance to earn postsecondary credit with a passing score will need to test in September.
Graduating seniors may either take the test at the high school they were enrolled in, or they can test at the closest community college or TCAT.
Graduating seniors should contact the admissions office at their post-secondary institution for guidance on registering for fall classes.

In accordance with Executive Order #22 issued by Governor Lee which instructs us to limit essential activities to the greatest extent possible, we have received a waiver that will allow us to serve meals only on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays. Beginning next Wednesday, April 15, School Nutrition will serve two days worth of meals each Monday and Wednesday, and then the regular meals on Friday.

According to the regulations of the nutrition program, we are unable to provide meals on weekends or other days that are not scheduled school days on the board approved calendar. Therefore, we will not be able to serve meals on Friday, April 10 or Monday, April 13 as those days are previously scheduled holidays.

In preparation to make this transition, on Tuesday, April 14, we will serve grab and go meals in the car rider lanes at school sites only. There will not be neighborhood stops or bus route deliveries on Tuesday, April 14. Beginning Wednesday, April 15, we will resume bus route deliveries as mentioned above.

ATTENTION SENIORS - IMPORTANT TN PROMISE ELIGIBILITY INFORMATION
tnAchieves has extended the TN Promise mandatory webinar deadline to May 15, 2020. Any student whose mandatory meeting was scheduled after March 11, 2020 must watch the 37-minute webinar by 11:59 PM on May 15, 2020 in order to maintain TN Promise eligibility. Students who missed their assigned meeting prior to March 12, 2020 can view the webinar in order to reinstate TN Promise eligibility. Students will receive a confirmation of webinar completion the day after the student successfully watches the webinar. Please note that students can view the webinar via mobile device. If a student has any questions regarding the webinar, the student can contact tnAchieves directly.

post_text: The damage from Monday's tornado extended beyond just losing homes. Many families have been without electric and basic needs during this time. Our community has focused heavily on helping the families immediately effected by the storms. We realize that many families face struggles on a daily basis. With that being said, Cornerstone Elementary and Compassion Ministries would like to invite anyone who needs assistance to our distribution day on Wednesday, March 11, 2020 . This is our way to help all families in the Baxter Community. Please reach out to your neighbor and bring them. Let us help you! Our distribution hours will be from 9-2 & 4-6 p.m.. Call (931)858-9190 if transportation is an issue .

shared_text:
Barbara Greeson is with Jim Greeson and 3 others.
March 8 at 9:23 PM ·

Sometimes there are serendipitous moments when our WOW team just looks at one another and says, “WOW”. The Magic Treehouse book, Tornado Tuesday, was in a random tote of books we carried into Northeast Elementary on Friday. Coincidence, maybe. Serendipitous, at the least. A friend gave me a tee shirt that says, “Everyone is a reader. Some just haven’t found their favorite book yet.” Good books, fiction and nonfiction do more than develop comprehension skills and build vocabulary. Compassion, empathy, problem solving, imagination, and curiosity, are just a few thinking and social/emotional skills and goals we all have for our children. Good books and subsequent conversations with a child! ...And I just don’t believe the “Face in a Phone” method replaces it. #putnamstrong #read20 #putdownthephone

post_text: As crews continue to complete work in the affected area, a significant portion of Highway 70 will remain closed through the first part of this week. The only bus route that will be significantly affected by this closure is Bus 85. Our school transportation team has created new drop off and pick up points for students on that route. They are communicating the new stops to the families on the Bus 85 route throughout the day today. The alternate stops will also be posted on the school system FB page as well as the EMA FB page when finalized. If you ride Bus 85, or if you have been displaced and normally ride a bus, and have not been contacted, please reach out to the transportation department at (931) 526-9342.

post_text:
SCHOOL STATUS UPDATE: MONDAY, MARCH 9, 2020
Recovery from last week’s devastating storms will take weeks, months, and even years for some. For many, part of the healing process includes returning to a normal routine. To that end, all Putnam County Schools will re-open on Monday, March 9, 2020.

For those that have suffered a significant loss, we want you to know that your school community is ready to support you and your family however possible.

For both students and staff members, we will have additional counseling support available to those who need to speak to someone. To access this service, please let any teacher or staff member know and they will be able to assist in making contact with your school’s counseling center.

Barbara Greeson is with Jim Greeson and 5 others.
March 7 at 9:22 PM ·

The WOW Bus gave away a total of about 400 books on Thursday and Friday to kids at Baxter Primary School, Cornerstone Elementary, and Northeast Elementary School. This opportunity, so different from our previous events, happened because of the tragedy of the tornado early Tuesday morning.
Kids in the care of Putnam County School System on Thursday and Friday were engaged in any number of planned, fun activities while parents worked, while parents volunteered to help with tornado relief, or because their homes and lives had been disrupted by the storm. Just like in kindergarten, it’s time to hold hands and stick together.
#putnamstrong #wowbusgivesbooksandgetssmiles #readtwenty

Tammy Hoover
March 6 at 7:39 PM ·

Cornerstone Elementary would like to get communication out to anyone affected by the recent tornados. We have partnered with Compassion Ministries out of Knoxville and they will be bringing a tractor-trailer load of supplies ranging from linens, cleaning products, toiletries, food, and drinks. We plan on opening our gymnasium up for distribution on Wednesday, March 11, 2020. Our times to distribute will be from 9-2 and 4-6 for anyone who has a need. If you could please come during these set times, we will load you up. In addition, we have a supply room that has water, food, and personal hygiene items that can be picked up for weeks to come. If any family needs assistance, please call (931) 858-9190 and let us know your needs. If transportation is an issue, we can deliver it to you. We love you and we will get through this together.

Shared at the request of Cookeville Police Chief Randy Evans

Facebook Message for tornado site volunteers:

An overwhelming number of volunteers have traveled to the site of the tornados to provide cleanup help for the victims of this devastating storm. While this represents our community well and shows the true volunteer spirit of our Upper Cumberland citizens, we now ask that you please stay clear of the area. So many people have shown up to help that it has congested the area and emergency vehicles and workers are unable to get to the areas in need. In the coming days, there will be plenty of opportunities and our Emergency Management personnel will provide direction for volunteers wanting to help those in need.

Cookeville Police Chief,
Randy Evans

ALL PUTNAM COUNTY SCHOOLS WILL BE CLOSED Wednesday, March 4 - Friday, March 6. The District Offices will remain open.

School-Age Care (SAC) will be provided at Northeast Elementary School.

Beginning Thursday, March 5 and continuing Friday, March 6, Cane Creek Elementary School, Baxter Primary School, Cornerstone Elementary School, Upperman Middle School, and Upperman High School will be open from 9:00 a.m. - 2:00 p.m. for children of families directly impacted by the storms.

Bus transportation will be provided from designated shelters to these school sites.

Breakfast and lunch will be available for students at these sites.

Current plans are for all PCSS schools to reopen on a regular schedule on Monday, March 9. Any need to change these plans will be communicated to families on Sunday evening.

For the most up-to-date general information, check the
@Putnam County Emergency Management Agency Facebook page.

Updates regarding Putnam County Schools will be posted on our Facebook page.

ALL PUTNAM COUNTY SCHOOLS WILL BE CLOSED Today -- Friday, FEBRUARY 28, 2020.

School-Age Care (SAC) will be provided at Northeast Elementary School for participating families; 6:00 AM - 6:00 PM

The uncertainty of this morning’s forecast creates concern for transporting students safely to and from school today. While the approaching system may amount to little, if any, accumulation, I am concerned about students being on the roads in buses or cars at the time the front is predicted to move through our area, especially in the higher elevations. Forecasts call for around 1” inch of accumulation of ice and snow beginning around 7:00 am and continuing through noon today. I don’t believe it is in the best interest of students and families to take a chance on safely traveling to and from school.

Everyone be safe today and enjoy the long weekend. Hopefully, we will be ready to return to school next week with a focus on learning!

Elementary school zone lines for the eleven elementary schools in Putnam County have been adjusted for the 2020-21 school year. Letters will be sent home with your child on Friday, Feb. 14, 2020, to explain the changes.

You can see the new zoning based on your home address at https://app.guidek12.com/putnamtn/school_search/2020/

The zoning policy is based upon a student’s residential address. The elementary school to middle school “feeder patterns” currently in place have not been changed, however, middle and high school zone boundaries will change slightly due to the adjustments to the elementary zone lines. Transportation routing for the 2020-2021 school year and beyond will follow the 2020-2021 zone patterns.

post_text:
Due to the increasing number of students, teachers, and support staff who continue to be affected by a variety of seasonal illnesses, ALL Putnam County schools will be closed on Monday, February 3 and Tuesday, February 4, 2020.

ALL PUTNAM COUNTY SCHOOLS WILL BE CLOSED on Monday, February 3 and Tuesday, February 4, 2020. The District Offices will remain open.

NO School Age Care (SAC) will be provided during this time.

TSSAA related High School athletic contests may continue at the discretion of the principals and athletic directors. All other school-related activities will be canceled on Monday, February 3 and Tuesday, February 4.

We hope that everyone will take this opportunity to remain at home, rest, and recuperate. We look forward to everyone returning to school healthy and ready to learn next Wednesday, February 5!

Everyone have a good evening, take care, and be well.
